  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most sellers think about their property from their own perspective: what they love about it, what they paid for it, what they have spent on it over the years. This is natural, but it is not particularly useful when preparing for a sale. The more useful frame is to think from the buyer's perspective. Who is most likely to pay the most for this property, and what does that buyer care about most? Getting this right shapes how you prepare, how you present, and how your agent positions the home in the market.</p>

      <p>Brisbane's inner-east suburbs attract a distinct and identifiable buyer pool. The corridor from Woolloongabba through Morningside, Hawthorne, Bulimba, and Norman Park to Camp Hill, Coorparoo, and Carina draws buyers with specific profiles, specific motivations, and specific price sensitivities. Understanding those profiles is part of what a good local agent brings to the conversation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The family upgrader</h2>
      <p>The most active buyer type in Brisbane's inner-east housing market is the family upgrader: couples, typically in their mid-thirties to mid-forties, often with one or two children or with children on the way, who are selling a smaller property or an apartment and moving up into a family home. They are usually owner-occupiers already. They have equity. They have done the research. And they are comparing your property directly against three or four others they have walked through in recent weeks.</p>

      <p>School catchments are the single most consistently important factor for this buyer type in the inner east. State school catchments for Cannon Hill Anglican College, Balmoral State High, Churchie, and the primary feeder schools into the better-regarded state secondary options drive enormous demand within those boundaries. A property in the right catchment can command a meaningful premium over a comparable property 800 metres away that misses it. If your property is in a desirable catchment, this is not incidental to the marketing, it is central to it.</p>

      <p>Family upgraders also care about liveability: the practicality of the floor plan, storage, outdoor space, access to parks, the length and ease of the commute to the CBD. They are increasingly comfortable with the idea of buying and renovating, particularly at the entry level of the family home market, but they want to understand what they are taking on. Uncertainty is more damaging than disclosed work. A home that needs work but has a clear, honest picture of what that work involves is easier for this buyer to price than one where they cannot tell what is behind the walls.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The downsizer</h2>
      <p>The second significant buyer type in the inner east is the empty nester or early retiree downsizing from a larger family home, often in the same general area or from a slightly further-out Brisbane suburb. They are typically cashed-up, often buying without needing finance or with very little leverage, and they are motivated by lifestyle: proximity to the river, walkability to cafes and restaurants, lower maintenance than the home they are leaving.</p>

      <p>Downsizers are often the strongest buyers for well-presented townhouses, courtyard homes, and smaller Queenslanders in the 2 to 3 bedroom range on compact lots. They tend to be less concerned about school catchments and more concerned about the quality of finish, the ease of maintenance, and the feeling of the neighbourhood. They have frequently been watching a specific area for some time before they buy.</p>

      <p>This buyer type is also more likely to pay a premium for turnkey presentation. They have usually come from a home they have lived in for a long time and maintained well. A property that needs immediate cosmetic work is often less appealing to them than to a younger buyer who views renovation as an opportunity to add their own stamp. If your property is well-finished and well-maintained, emphasising that directly to the downsizer demographic in your marketing is worthwhile.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The investor</h2>
      <p>Investment buyers are present in the inner east but are rarely the strongest buyer for a well-presented family home or a desirable lifestyle property. The inner east's land values, driven by owner-occupier demand, mean that gross rental yields are typically not compelling enough to attract pure investment buyers who are optimising for yield. That buyer pool tends to look elsewhere.</p>

      <p>Where investment buyers do compete strongly in the inner east is for properties with genuine development potential, particularly on larger or corner lots in areas where character overlays do not prevent subdivision or secondary dwellings, and for well-located apartments or townhouses that generate strong rental returns relative to purchase price. For these property types, including investor-specific considerations in your marketing, such as current rental income, proximity to employment centres, and infrastructure such as future public transport, is relevant.</p>

      <p>For the majority of inner-east family homes, investors are not your primary audience. Positioning a campaign primarily toward investors for a property that is likely to attract the strongest bids from owner-occupiers is a strategic error. Your marketing should be calibrated to the buyer type that will pay the most, and for most inner-east properties, that is the family upgrader or the downsizer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Interstate and international buyers</h2>
      <p>Since 2020, Brisbane's inner east has seen sustained interest from buyers relocating from Sydney and Melbourne, attracted by the relative affordability of comparable lifestyle properties. This buyer cohort has been a material factor in the price growth of the past several years and remains active, though at a lower level than the peak relocation activity of 2021 to 2023.</p>

      <p>Interstate buyers often have higher price ceilings than comparable local buyers, because they are benchmarking against Sydney or Melbourne prices rather than Brisbane prices. They also tend to move quickly once they have identified a property they want, because they are typically making a trip specifically to purchase and do not have the same ability to attend multiple inspections over a number of weeks. Digital marketing that gives interstate buyers a strong sense of the property before they visit is particularly important when this buyer type is in play.</p>

      <p>International buyers, including Australian expats and foreign residents with the right to purchase, are a smaller but occasionally significant cohort for premium inner-east properties. They tend to require more information about the suburb, the schools, and the commute than a buyer who already knows the area, and a good agent will understand how to present the property to this audience effectively.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How understanding buyer types shapes preparation</h2>
      <p>Once you know who is most likely to buy your property and what they care about, the practical implications for preparation become clearer. A family home in a top school catchment should be marketed with that catchment front and centre, and the floor plan should present as functional and practical for a family rather than styled for a magazine shoot that obscures how people actually live. A low-maintenance townhouse targeting downsizers should be impeccably presented and finished, with every detail attended to.</p>

      <p>The same logic applies to what you fix before you sell and what you leave. A family upgrader who plans to renovate the kitchen anyway is not likely to pay significantly more because you replaced it with a mid-range finish before selling. But that same buyer may adjust their offer materially if the roof needs attending to or the bathroom has a visible water damage issue. Understanding what your buyer type weighs heavily versus lightly helps you spend your preparation budget in the right places.</p>

